<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-266-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 266 650.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  March 20 1990 v4 n11 p28(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's not a leap, but IIfx keeps the faith. (new MacintoshIIfx)(Editorial) (editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh IIfx (Microcomputer) (innovations).andO;Topic:     New ProductPerformance ImprovementProduct DelayMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The introduction of the Mac IIfx this week may not appear like a significantleap forward, but if you look closely, you'll see that it has some worthwhiletechnology.andM;First, the IIfx keeps the faith.andP;  It is compatible with the vast majority ofapplications that run on the Mac Plus through the Mac IIci.andP;  If you wereexpecting some extraordinary technological breakthrough, it almost certainlywould not run the thousands of existing applications.andP;  Secondly, it includeseight new custom chips and a low parts count, which shows that Apple isspending a lot of money and effort on miniaturization and integration.andM;Third, the IIfx is the first Mac to offer direct memory access andspecialized I/O processors, which are fully integrated into the CPU and helpmaintain a zero-wait-state system.andM;These facets of the IIfx, and others such as self-configuring video cards andthe system software, may not be overwhelming by themselves, but collectivelythey show what makes the Macintosh different from its competitors.andM;The only problem is that the IIfx should have been out last year.andP;  Reducingthe time it takes to bring products to market is a key issue that Apple needsto resolve.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>